encyclopedia</DIV>\t\t\t\t<DIV id=\"contentSub\"></DIV>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<DIV id=\"jump-to-nav\" class=\"mw-jump\">\n\t\t\t\t\tJump to:\t\t\t\t\t<A href=\"#mw-head\">navigation</A>, \t\t\t\t\t<A href=\"#p-search\">search</A>\n\t\t\t\t</DIV>\n\t\t\t\t<DIV id=\"mw-content-text\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\" class=\"mw-content-ltr\"><DIV class=\"mw-parser-output\"><P>The <B>Majority Leader of the New York State Senate</B> is elected by the majority of the members of the <A href=\"/wiki/New_York_State_Senate\" title=\"New York State Senate\">New York State Senate</A>. The position usually coincides with the title of <B>Temporary President of the State Senate</B>, who presides over the session of the State Senate if the <A href=\"/wiki/Lieutenant_Governor_of_New_York\" title=\"Lieutenant Governor of New York\">Lieutenant Governor of New York</A> (who is <A href=\"/wiki/Ex_officio\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ex officio\">ex officio</A> President of the State Senate) is absent. The Temporary President of the State Senate becomes Acting Lieutenant Governor for the remainder of the unexpired term in case of a vacancy in the office of lieutenant governor.<SUP id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-1\">[1]</A></SUP> In case of a vacancy in the offices of both the governor and lieutenant governor at the same time, the Temporary President of the State Senate becomes Acting Governor. If the double vacancy occurs until three months before the mid-term state elections,<SUP id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-2\">[2]</A></SUP> a special election for <A href=\"/wiki/Governor_of_New_York\" title=\"Governor of New York\">Governor of New York</A> and Lieutenant Governor is held. If the double vacancy occurs later, the Temporary President of the State Senate acts as governor until the end of the unexpired term. The Temporary President of the State Senate retains both his majority leadership and his seat in the State Senate while acting as lieutenant governor or governor.</P>\n<P>There was a lengthy dispute over the leadership of the Senate during June and July 2009. On June 8, 2009, <A href=\"/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)\" title=\"Democratic Party (United States)\">Democrats</A> <A href=\"/wiki/Hiram_Monserrate\" title=\"Hiram Monserrate\">Hiram Monserrate</A> and <A href=\"/wiki/Pedro_Espada,_Jr.\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pedro Espada, Jr.\">Pedro Espada, Jr.</A>, joined the 30 Republican members of the State Senate to attempt to issue a motion to replace current Majority Leader <A href=\"/wiki/Malcolm_Smith_(US_politician)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Malcolm Smith (US politician)\">Malcolm Smith</A> with Minority Leader <A href=\"/wiki/Dean_Skelos\" title=\"Dean Skelos\">Dean Skelos</A>.<SUP id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-3\">[3]</A></SUP> Following the precedent of 1913, the temporary presidency and the majority leadership would have been separated again under this scenario. Since the office of Lieutenant Governor fell vacant after Lt. Gov. <A href=\"/wiki/David_Paterson\" title=\"David Paterson\">David Paterson</A> succeeded to the governorship upon Gov. <A href=\"/wiki/Eliot_Spitzer\" title=\"Eliot Spitzer\">Eliot Spitzer</A>&#39;s resignation, the majority leaders (Bruno, Skelos and Smith) have acted as lieutenant governors. The motions put forward on June 8 also sought to select Pedro Espada as Temporary President of the State Senate, which would have installed him as acting lieutenant governor. The Democrats have disputed the legitimacy of the motions put forward on June 8. The New York State Senate has been providing a <A rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nysenate.gov/blogs/2009/jun/11/smith-v-espada-coverage-and-materials-updated-61309\">running update</A> of the legal proceedings since June 11, 2009. The dispute ended July 9, 2009, when Senator Espada announced he would return to the Democratic caucus and take on the position of majority leader, while it was also announced that former majority leader Malcolm Smith had assumed the title of president pro tempore, and John Sampson would serve as Democratic conference leader with the understanding he would assume the presidency at an undetermined future date. Following the 2010 election and the Republican victory in the Senate, Senator <A href=\"/wiki/Dean_Skelos\" title=\"Dean Skelos\">Dean Skelos</A> from Long Island served as both Temporary President and Majority Leader, but resigned in May 2015 in the midst of corruption charges. The current majority leader, or president, is John J. Flanagan.</P>\n<P></P>\n<DIV id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\">\n<DIV class=\"toctitle\">\n<H2>Contents</H2>\n<SPAN class=\"toctoggle\"> [<A role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"togglelink\">hide</A>] </SPAN></DIV>\n<UL>\n<LI class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><A href=\"#History\"><SPAN class=\"tocnumber\">1</SPAN> <SPAN class=\"toctext\">History</SPAN></A></LI>\n<LI class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><A href=\"#Presidents_pro_tempore_1874_-_1938\"><SPAN class=\"tocnumber\">2</SPAN> <SPAN class=\"toctext\">Presidents pro tempore 1874 - 1938</SPAN></A></LI>\n<LI class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><A href=\"#Majority_Leaders_since_1939\"><SPAN class=\"tocnumber\">3</SPAN> <SPAN class=\"toctext\">Majority Leaders since 1939</SPAN></A></LI>\n<LI class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><A href=\"#Notes\"><SPAN class=\"tocnumber\">4</SPAN> <SPAN class=\"toctext\">Notes</SPAN></A></LI>\n</UL>\n</DIV>\n<P></P>\n<H2><SPAN class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</SPAN><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection\"><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</SPAN><A href=\"/w/index.php?title=Majority_Leader_of_the_New_York_State_Senate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</A><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>\n<P>The position of <B>President pro tempore of the New York State Senate</B> was created as a standing office by a constitutional amendment in 1873. The President pro tempore was elected for the duration of the biennial senatorial term which comprised two sessions, the first in an even-numbered year, the other in the following odd-numbered year.</P>\n<P>Before this time, a President pro tempore was elected only in case of vacancy (the President pro tem acting as lieutenant governor for the remainder of the term), or if the lieutenant governor was absent. In practice, this new arrangement transferred much power from the lieutenant governor to the President pro tempore, whose political position became comparable to that of the <A href=\"/wiki/Speaker_of_the_New_York_State_Assembly\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Speaker of the New York State Assembly\">Speaker of the New York State Assembly</A>.</P>\n<P>After the impeachment of Governor <A href=\"/wiki/William_Sulzer\" title=\"William Sulzer\">William Sulzer</A> in October 1913, Lt. Gov. <A href=\"/wiki/Martin_H._Glynn\" title=\"Martin H. Glynn\">Martin H. Glynn</A> became governor, and President pro tempore <A href=\"/wiki/Robert_F._Wagner\" title=\"Robert F. Wagner\">Robert F. Wagner</A> became acting lieutenant governor. At the time Wagner – as acting lieutenant governor – was considered to be President of the Senate and it was deemed necessary to elect another member as President pro tempore/Majority Leader,<SUP id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-4\">[4]</A></SUP> and <A href=\"/wiki/John_F._Murtaugh\" title=\"John F. Murtaugh\">John F. Murtaugh</A> was chosen.</P>\n<P>The precedent of 1913–14 caused some confusion after the death of Lt. Gov. <A href=\"/wiki/Thomas_W._Wallace\" title=\"Thomas W. Wallace\">Thomas W. Wallace</A> in 1943. It was unclear if the Majority Leader had to give up his post upon becoming acting lieutenant governor, and if such an acting lieutenant governor became President of the Senate for the remainder of the unexpired term.<SUP id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-5\">[5]</A></SUP></P>\n<P>Traditionally, the positions of acting lieutenant governor and acting governor were considered to be tied to the post of Majority Leader. Kaa breaks down the wall of the building in which Mowgli is imprisoned in and uses his serpentine <A href=\"/wiki/Hypnosis\" title=\"Hypnosis\">hypnosis</A> to draw the monkeys toward his waiting jaws. Bagheera and Baloo are also hypnotized, but Mowgli is immune because he is human and breaks the spell on his friends.</P>\n<P>In <I><A href=\"/wiki/The_Second_Jungle_Book\" title=\"The Second Jungle Book\">The Second Jungle Book</A></I>, Kaa appears in the first half of the story &quot;The King&#39;s <A href=\"/wiki/Ankus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ankus\">Ankus</A>&quot;. After Kaa and Mowgli spend some time relaxing, bathing and wrestling, Kaa persuades Mowgli to visit a treasure chamber guarded by an old <A href=\"/wiki/Cobra_(snake)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cobra (snake)\">cobra</A> beneath the same Cold Lairs. The cobra tries to kill Mowgli but its poison has dried up. Mowgli takes a jeweled item away as a souvenir, not realizing the trouble it will cause them, and Kaa departs.</P>\n<P>In &quot;<A href=\"/wiki/Red_Dog_(Kipling_short_story)\" title=\"Red Dog (Kipling short story)\">Red Dog</A>&quot;, Mowgli asks Kaa for help when his wolf pack is threatened by rampaging <A href=\"/wiki/Dhole\" title=\"Dhole\">dholes</A> (the red dogs of the title). Kaa, Baloo and Bagheera sing for Mowgli in &quot;The Outsong&quot;, a poem and the ending of &quot;The Spring Running&quot;.</P>\n<H2><SPAN class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Disney_films\">Disney films</SPAN><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection\"><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</SPAN><A href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kaa&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Disney films\">edit</A><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>\n<H3><SPAN class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Disney_animated_films\">Disney animated films</SPAN><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection\"><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</SPAN><A href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kaa&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Disney animated films\">edit</A><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>\n<P>In <A href=\"/wiki/The_Jungle_Book_(1967_film)\" title=\"The Jungle Book (1967 film)\">the 1967 Disney film</A>, Kaa is markedly different from the Kipling character. Rather than being a mentor, he appears as a minor <A href=\"/wiki/Antagonist\" title=\"Antagonist\">antagonist</A> who twice manages to trap Mowgli in his coils in an attempt to eat him. He does this through the use of hypnotic eyes as opposed to the original version, in which he uses a serpentine dance to control his prey. Both of his attempts to eat Mowgli end in comical failure because he is interrupted right before he can swallow him. Kaa is depicted as cowardly, attempting to curry favor with Shere Khan whenever he is around.</P>\n<P>Voice actor <A href=\"/wiki/Sterling_Holloway\" title=\"Sterling Holloway\">Sterling Holloway</A> decided to give Kaa a <A href=\"/wiki/Lisp\" title=\"Lisp\">lisp</A>, a condition that composers the <A href=\"/wiki/Sherman_Brothers\" title=\"Sherman Brothers\">Sherman Brothers</A> brought into the character&#39;s song in <I>The Jungle Book</I>, &quot;<A href=\"/wiki/Trust_in_Me_(The_Python%27s_Song)\" title=\"Trust in Me (The Python&#39;s Song)\">Trust in Me</A>&quot;.<SUP id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-1\">[1]</A></SUP></P>\n<P>This particular version of Kaa drew inspiration from previous Disney characters that followed a similar trope, such as Tick-Tock the Crocodile from <I><A href=\"/wiki/Peter_Pan_(1953_film)\" title=\"Peter Pan (1953 film)\">Peter Pan</A></I> and the Wolf from <I><A href=\"/wiki/The_Sword_in_the_Stone_(film)\" title=\"The Sword in the Stone (film)\">The Sword in the Stone</A></I>. Both are fixated on a specific character (namely <A href=\"/wiki/Captain_Hook\" title=\"Captain Hook\">Captain Hook</A> and <A href=\"/wiki/King_Arthur\" title=\"King Arthur\">Wart</A>, respectively) as food and comically attempt to eat them throughout the film, without success.</P>\n<P>In <I><A href=\"/wiki/The_Jungle_Book_2\" title=\"The Jungle Book 2\">The Jungle Book 2</A></I>, Kaa - now voiced by <A href=\"/wiki/Jim_Cummings\" title=\"Jim Cummings\">Jim Cummings</A> - reappears in a smaller role. He is first seen attempting to eat the man-cub as Baloo and Mowgli reprise &quot;<A href=\"/wiki/The_Bare_Necessities\" title=\"The Bare Necessities\">The Bare Necessities</A>&quot;, but is thwarted each time. He eventually gives up, swearing he will &quot;never again associate with man-cubs&quot;. Kaa then comes across Shanti, who is lost in the jungle in search for Mowgli. He successfully hypnotizes her and attempts to eat her, but is stopped by Ranjan. He is last seen being interrogated by Shere Khan about Mowgli&#39;s whereabouts, lying to the tiger that the boy is heading for the swamp.</P>\n<H3><SPAN class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"1994_live-action_film\">1994 live-action film</SPAN><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection\"><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</SPAN><A href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kaa&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: 1994 live-action film\">edit</A><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>\n<P>A far more menacing incarnation of the character appeared in the <A href=\"/wiki/The_Jungle_Book_(1994_film)\" title=\"The Jungle Book (1994 film)\">1994 live-action adaptation</A>. He was brought to life using an actual anaconda, but the bulk of his appearances were made using a mixture of CGI and animatronics. In the film, Kaa seems to serve <A href=\"/wiki/King_Louie\" title=\"King Louie\">King Louie</A>, killing any intruders to the city when Louie summons him. Kaa attacks Mowgli inside the monkey city by tackling him into the moat and attempting to drown him, but Mowgli wounds him with a bejewelled dagger, forcing the python to flee in a pool of his own blood.</P>\n<P>By the time Mowgli returns to the city with Captain William Boone (the main villain of the film) and Kitty, Kaa has fully healed from their prior confrontation. After defeating Boone, Mowgli flees with Kitty when he hears King Louie summoning the python. Boone starts gathering as much treasure as he can, but notices that the monkeys have gone silent; Kaa suddenly appears, then scares the injured Boone into the moat, where the heavy load of treasure he is carrying weighs him straight to the bottom. Desperately trying to struggle free, Boone sees the skeletal remains of Kaa&#39;s past victims just seconds before the villain finally meets his death by the python.</P>\n<H3><SPAN class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"2016_live-action_film\">2016 live-action film</SPAN><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection\"><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</SPAN><A href=\"/w/index.php?title=Kaa&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: 2016 live-action film\">edit</A><SPAN class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</SPAN></SPAN></H3>\n<P>Kaa appeared in Walt Disney Pictures&#39; <A href=\"/wiki/The_Jungle_Book_(2016_film)\" title=\"The Jungle Book (2016 film)\">live-action adaptation of the animated film</A>, directed by <A href=\"/wiki/Jon_Favreau\" title=\"Jon Favreau\">Jon Favreau</A>. This version of Kaa is female and is voiced by <A href=\"/wiki/Scarlett_Johansson\" title=\"Scarlett Johansson\">Scarlett Johansson</A>. This film&#39;s Kaa (like the previous Disney incarnations voiced by <A href=\"/wiki/Sterling_Holloway\" title=\"Sterling Holloway\">Sterling Holloway</A>, <A href=\"/wiki/Hal_Smith_(actor)\" title=\"Hal Smith (actor)\">Hal Smith</A>, and <A href=\"/wiki/Jim_Cummings\" title=\"Jim Cummings\">Jim Cummings</A>) desires to eat Mowgli. Luring him in by promising to keep him safe, she hypnotizes him and reveals that the boy came to live in the jungle when Shere Khan killed his father as they were travelling between villages and Bagheera found him. She also reveals to him the power of the &quot;Red Flower&quot; (fire) and its dangers in her vision. During her storytelling, she attempts to devour him, but Baloo spots and rescues Mowgli, denying her of her meal. She is not seen again for the rest of the film, though during the end credits, she is heard singing &quot;<A href=\"/wiki/Trust_in_Me_(The_Python%27s_Song)\" title=\"Trust in Me (The Python&#39;s Song)\">Trust in Me</A>&quot;.</P>\n<P>In an interview, Johansson elaborated on Kaa, saying that she uses both her voice and hypnotic gaze to entrance Mowgli so that he cannot resist her embrace. She also says Kaa uses her story-telling to seduce and entrap Mowgli and describes Kaa as a &quot;window into Mowgli&#39;s past&quot;. She notes that the way Kaa moves is &quot;very alluring&quot;, describing it as &quot;almost coquettish&quot;.<SUP id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><A href=\"#cite_note-2\">[2]</A></SUP> Johansson also sings the song &quot;Trust in Me&quot; in the film; she described her thoughts on the song: &quot;It&#39;s a strange melody.
